{
  "text": "Cannabinoid withdrawal produces a marked reduction of electrophysiological activity in NAcc-projecting dopamine (DA) containing neurons of the rat midbrain [CITATION_1] and a reduction of DA outflow in the NAcc shell [CITATION_2] . This functional evidence suggests that cannabinoids withdrawal may structurally alter cellular elements of the mesolimbic system, as it was recently shown for opiate dependence [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Accordingly, chronic [CITATION_6] TetraHydroCannabinol (THC) treatment has been shown to increase the length of the dendrites as well as the number of dendritic branches in both the shell *Address correspondence to this author at the Dept. of Drug Sciences, Univ. of Sassari, Via Muroni 23/A, 07100 Sassari, Italy; Tel: 079 228714; Fax: 079 228715; E-mail: dsfdiana@uniss.it of the NAcc and the medial prefrontal cortex, though not in other brain areas [CITATION_7] . However, since morphological evaluations were made long after drug discontinuation (30 days), it is impossible to ascertain the relationship between onset of withdrawal and structural changes.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "24780855",
